          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":60,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"24 km easy long run at 5:07–5:39/km. Keep effort conversational throughout — this is aerobic foundation work, not a fitness test. Hydrate well and practice your race-day fueling strategy.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Sleep and nutrition are doing real work today — this is where adaptation happens.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"30–45 min low-impact cross-training (cycling, swimming, or yoga). Keep heart rate easy. This supports aerobic base without adding run-specific load.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"10 km easy at 5:07–5:39/km. This is a recovery-quality run — if your legs feel heavy from Sunday, lean toward the slower end of the range.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Let Tuesday's cross-training and Wednesday's easy run settle in before the quality work ahead.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"12 km total: 3 km warm-up at easy pace, 6 km at threshold pace (4:16/km), 3 km cool-down. Threshold work builds your lactate ceiling — the physiological engine behind your marathon goal.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"14 km easy at 5:07–5:39/km. A moderate-distance easy run to round out the week's volume. Keep it genuinely easy — this is not a tempo in disguise.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to Week 1, Priya. Your recent training shows you're already handling solid volume — 60 km weeks, a 26 km long run, and quality sessions at marathon and threshold pace. That's a strong foundation to build from. This first week mirrors your current load intentionally: we're not adding stress yet, we're establishing the rhythm of a 4-day structure with one quality session (Thursday tempo) and a long run anchoring the week on Sunday. The cross-training slot on Tuesday gives your legs a break from impact while keeping aerobic stimulus ticking. Your 3:15 marathon goal requires sustaining 4:37/km — your current VDOT of 49.7 puts that goal well within reach with consistent, progressive training over the next 24 weeks. What questions do you have before we get started?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
